<item>
            <title>[SEC-3030] Reduce in memory lifetime of passwords</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-3030</link>
                <project id="10040" key="SEC">Spring Security</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The entire problem is described on SO &lt;a href=&quot;http://stackoverflow.com/a/31249173/206466&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://stackoverflow.com/a/31249173/206466&lt;/a&gt; . But the short of it is, with the G1 collector and String Deduplication turned on, how long will &quot;password123&quot; remain in memory? potentially too long, especially with features like &quot;remote debugging over http&quot; on their way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One proposed answer would be to salt (I suggest prefixed with csrftoken) the password string. Spring Security could introduce a PasswordCharSequence that would safely strip the salt after verification for the (Bcrypt) PasswordEncoder .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just an idea, maybe it&apos;s not worth the effort.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
